Background of the Data

Two files containing data about the content of streaming services were downloaded from Kaggle: Disney+ Movies and TV Shows and TV shows on Netflix, Prime Video, Hulu and Disney+. You can read about them there, including variable definitions, sources, when they were created, and other information. Read the two datasets from the data_raw folder and use skim() to explore their structures.

Analyses

Clean, Tidy, and Save the Data

Dataset #1: Disney+ Data

The Disney+ dataset contains a variable that gives information about the rating for each program offering. Convert that variable into a factor that puts the ratings in (roughly) ascending order of age restriction/audience: TV-Y, TV-Y7, TV-Y7-FV, TV-G, G, TV-PG, PG, PG-13, TV-14. Delete the show_id, director, cast, and description variables. You should be able to do this all in one piped sequence.

ratings <- disney_data %>%
  mutate(rating = factor(rating, levels = c("TV-Y", "TV-Y7", "TV-Y7-FV", "TV-G", "G", "TV-PG", "PG", "PG-13", "TV-14")))  %>%
  select(c(-show_id, -director, -cast, -description))

Dataset #2: Streaming TV Data

Perform the following manipulations to tidy the streaming TV data for analysis. You should be able to do this all in one piped sequence.

  • Pivot the Netflix, Hulu, Prime Video, and Disney+ variables into two columns called Service (containing the name of the streaming service) and YesNo (containing the 0/1 values from the original columns).
  • Filter the data set to remove any row where YesNo == 0 (i.e., a show is not on the service).
  • Separate the IMDb variable to split each show’s actual rating from the maximum possible rating of 10.
  • Convert the show’s actual IMDB rating into a numerical variable and get rid of the column containing 10.
  • Separate the Rotten Tomatoes variable to split each show’s actual rating from the maximum possible rating of 100.
  • Convert the show’s actual Rotten Tomatoes rating into a numerical variable and get rid of the column containing 100.
tv_streaming <- streaming_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("Netflix", "Hulu", "Prime.Video", "Disney."), 
    names_to = "Service", 
    values_to = "YesNo") %>%
  filter(YesNo != 0) %>%
  separate(col = IMDb, into = c("IMDBscore", "IMDBmax"), sep = "/") %>%
  select(-IMDBmax) %>%
  mutate(IMDBscore = as.numeric(IMDBscore)) %>%
  separate(col = Rotten.Tomatoes, into = c("rottenscore", "rottenmax"), sep = "/") %>%
  select(-rottenmax) %>%
  mutate(rottenscore = as.numeric(rottenscore))

Save the Formatted Data Files

Save both data files in a single.RData file in the data_tidy folder.

save(tv_streaming, ratings, file = "../data_tidy/bothDataFiles.Rmd")

Analysis 1: Disney Content & Release Years

This analysis uses Data set #1.

Release Years by Program Type—Plot #1

Create a violin plot of release_year (x axis) grouped by type of program (y axis) for programs on Disney+. Add a box plot inside the violin plot. Re-scale the X axis so that tick marks appear at whole-decade intervals (e.g., 1980, 1990, 2000). Include an informative title and axis labels. Add at least two other types of formatting to enhance the effectiveness and/or appearance of your plot (e.g., themes, colors, etc).

ggplot(ratings, aes(release_year, type)) + 
  geom_violin(fill = "Blue", alpha = .5) +
  geom_boxplot(width = .1, fill = "Red", outlier.size = 2) +
 
  labs(title = "Type of Programs based on Release Year", x = "Release Year", y = "Type of Program") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 1920, to = 2030, by = 10))

Release Years by Program Type—Plot #2

Create a histogram for release_year with type as a fill variable. Choose a reasonable number of bins or bin width. Re-scale the X axis so that tick marks appear at whole-decade intervals (e.g., 1980, 1990, 2000). Scale the Y axis to have reasonably spaced tick marks. Add vertical lines with annotations to indicate the debuts of the Disney Brothers Cartoon Studio (1923), the Disney Channel on TV (1983), and Disney+ streaming service (2019). Include an informative title and axis labels. Delete the title “type” from the legend. Add at least two other types of formatting to enhance the effectiveness and/or appearance of your plot (e.g., themes, colors, etc).

ggplot(ratings, aes(release_year, fill = type)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 25, color = "black") + 
    scale_fill_brewer() +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
    theme(legend.title=element_blank()) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(1923,1983,2019), color = c("Blue", "Orange", "Red"), linetype = "dashed") + 
  annotate("text", x = 1930, y = -10, label =  "Cartoon Studio Debut") +
annotate("text", x = 1983, y = -10, label = "Disney Channel Debut") +
annotate("text", x = 2019, y = -10, label = "Disney+ Debut") +
    labs(title = "Disney Release Dates", x = "Release Year", y = "Type") + 
scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 1920, to = 2030, by = 10))

Release Years by Program Type—Summary

Create a quantitative summary of release_year by program type that shows the oldest release year, the median release year, and the newest release year for each group of programs (i.e., movies and TV shows).

ratings_summary <- ratings %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(oldest = min(release_year),
            median = median(release_year),
            newest = max(release_year))

Analysis 2: Disney Content & Ratings

This analysis uses Data set #1.

Create a horizontal bar plot to show the frequencies of the various rating categories for programs on Disney+ (i.e., use y = rather than x = for the variable you are plotting). You will need to remove a couple NA values before plotting Facet by type so that you have side-by-side plots for the two different program types. Add an informative title and axis labels, as well as at least two other types of useful formatting.

use is.na

ratingsorderNoNA <- filter(ratings, !is.na(rating))

ggplot(ratingsorderNoNA, aes(y = rating)) + 
    geom_bar(fill = "pink") +
scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel2") +
    labs(title = "Ratings on Disney+", x = "Amount", y = "Rating") +

Questions

Question 1: Based on your plots, make five informational statements or comparisons regarding the Disney+ streaming service.

ANSWER

  1. The number of Disney releases skyrocketed once Disney Channel had their debut.

  2. There is a significantly greater amount of movies on Disney+ that are rated TV-G and PG than TV shows on Disney+.

  3. Disney+ has the smallest amount of TV Shows on their platform compared to Netflix, Hulu, and Prime Video.

  4. After the debut of Disney+, the amount of TV Shows produced by Disney decreased quite a bit.

  5. Compared to the other 3 streaming services, Disney+ had the second lowest median Rotten Tomatoes score.

Question 2: What other data would you like to have, or which existing variables would you like to see transformed, if you were going to do further explorations or visualizations? Give at least two examples.

ANSWER

We would’ve liked to see the duration variable in the ratings order data set transformed into something numerical rather than just having it as a character value. We also would’ve liked to see data from at least one more streaming service such as Paramount+ or HBO Max.

Question 3: Explain the rationale behind the choices you made with regard to plot type, formatting, and so on, when you created Analysis 4. What motivated your decisions with regard to this plot?

ANSWER

We wanted to see how strong the correlation was between shows with high IMDB scores vs. shows with high rotten tomato score, and if a show with a higher IMBD score meant for certain that it’d have a higher rotten tomato score. We also added the color aesthetic and changed the size of the data points to make the graph easier to read, since many of the points were jumbled together.
